<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="423" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,151,1508]" pageId="22" pageNumber="423">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1304,1328]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="423" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
Some minor variations exist in this new species: the left and middle triangular apical processes of the juxta are shorter, the left apical process has a small spine at base on outside and the right spine-like apical process is curved upward in the 
<typeStatus box="[528,628,1376,1400]" pageId="22" pageNumber="423">paratype</typeStatus>
. While the left and middle triangular apical processes of the juxta are longer, the left apical process has no spine at base and the right spine-like apical process is straight in the 
<typeStatus box="[1331,1433,1412,1436]" pageId="22" pageNumber="423">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="423" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,151,1508]" pageId="22" pageNumber="423">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1448,1472]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="423" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[839,965,1448,1472]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="423">palmifolius</emphasis>
(= maple leaf-like), referring to the shape of the juxta in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
